## Org GitHub policy (non-negotiable, not project-specific)

- All release code lives in the org's GitHub org, private by default.
  No repo is public without formal approval.
- No direct commits to `main`/`master` — all changes go through a PR.
- Every PR description states: what changed, why, how it affects
  deployment/behavior, and risks/dependencies.
- Reviewers who contribute code to a PR become co-authors and cannot
  approve it — a separate reviewer is required.
- `CODEOWNERS`, `README.md`, and `.gitignore` must exist within 6 hours
  of repo creation. `CODEOWNERS` must assign teams/groups, never
  individuals, and must never be left blank.
- Never store customer data or PII in the repo. Never use customer names
  in commits, PRs, branch names, or code variables.

## Conventions

- Language/framework: [<<COE TO UPDATE THIS FIELD>>]
- Testing: see `docs/testing.md` (created/maintained via the `test-strategy`
  skill). If it doesn't exist yet for this project, run `test-strategy` to
  set it up before assuming test expectations. Note: this is a pre-PR gap
  check, not a substitute for the org's required CI test/security-scan
  gate — both apply.
- PR checklist:
  - [ ] Tests pass locally (`pytest`)
  - [ ] `docs/testing.md` requirements met (run `test-strategy` if unsure)
  - [ ] `security-check` run — no secrets, customer data, or PII in the diff
  - [ ] No new dependencies without a note in the PR description
  - [ ] Docstrings added/updated for any new public functions
  - [ ] PR description includes: what changed, why, how it affects
        deployment, risks/dependencies (per org policy)
- Style/lint: `ruff` for linting + formatting, config in `pyproject.toml`
  (`ruff check .` and `ruff format .` before pushing)

## Security & compliance

- Before considering a task done or opening a PR, run a `security-check`
  pass on what changed (secrets, customer data/PII, new dependencies,
  new external calls, and — for new repos — required setup files).

## Architecture decisions

- Significant technical decisions live in `docs/adr/`, one file per
  decision. If you're about to make a call that a future teammate might
  reasonably question later, use the `adr` skill to record it.
- Read `docs/adr/` (most recent files first) before proposing a change to
  something that already has a documented decision behind it.

## New team members

- If someone says they're new to this repo, use the `onboard` skill to
  orient them rather than explaining ad hoc — keeps the answer consistent
  and grounded in what's actually documented. Note: `onboard` covers
  codebase orientation, not org-level GitHub access setup — point brand
  new hires at the org's access request process first if they don't have
  access yet.

## Solo/planning docs (optional, project-dependent)

- If this project also uses `docs/spec.md` / `docs/build/phase-N.md` for
  active planning, read them at session start. Not every team repo needs
  this — it's most useful for a project with a clear owner driving it,
  less so for a repo many people touch equally.
